snippet.textDisplay:
If you really look into the lyrics, you'll find that it was never about a man questioning the abrupt absence of a loved one nor him running away from the pain it has caused him inside. It was always about a man's lust and search for chicken. Allow me to elaborate:

"I fell for your magic, I tasted your skin"
- This line refers to Joji's lust for chicken, as evidenced by the line "I tasted your skin". His obsession for deliciously made chicken has made him unstable, teetering on the very threshold of insanity just to taste it again for one last time.

"And though this is tragic, atleast I found the end"
- This line denotes Joji's acceptance of the fact that he will never taste such amazing chicken again in his lifetime. But this is a smoke screen, for beneath the guise of contentment lies an unending appetite for chicken that will never be satiated.

"I witnessed your madness, you shed light on my sins"
- Joji grew mad over his search for a better fried chicken, but found no recompense for his efforts. Thus, I witnessed your madness actually denotes the insanity roiling inside of him instead of the fried chicken. The sin in question are two; lust and gluttony, for these sins are ever present when appeasing our own tastebuds.

"And if we share in this sadness, then where have you been?"
- At this point, Joji's delusion has seeped into the real world, thinking the fried chicken that he ate sympathized with his obsession to taste it again. He is questioning it and, in the course of questioning the chicken, his reality as well. This is further evidenced by the first two lines in the chorus.

"I know you're not in love, like you used to be"
- Again, he is attributing human emotion to his meal, further solidifying the theory that he has gone delusional in his search for delicious fried chicken.

"Guess I'm not the one, like you used to think"
- Same explanation as the verse above.

"So you just run"
- The meaning of this line is twofold; one referencing his insanity over fried chicken, the other describing the sensation of fried chicken entering his throat, fulfilling its purpose. "Run" in this context describes how quickly he gorges on the chicken.

"I know that I'm stuck in this misery"
- Like I said, he never reached the phase of acceptance and is merely providing a smoke screen to hide his true intentions, that is to search for the chicken he tasted before and witness its "magic" once more. He's eternally stuck in a cycle of self-hate and hunger, never able to satiate his tastebuds no matter how hard he tried.

"Guess I'm not enough like you use to think"
- More delusion for chicken. Pretty self-explanatory.

"So I'll just run"
- This time he is describing his search for delicious fried chicken, endlessly running towards whatever unknown banquet or buffet in order to find it again and taste it.

"You bathe in your victory, you blew out all my fuse"
- The "bathing" in this context, refers to the marinade used to season the chicken with. The taste proved to be otherworldy, prompting Joji to connect its flavor to the chicken's victory, for the chicken itself was delicious and even made more delicious because of the marinade. The next lines proves this even further, as the taste is so unique, so amazing, that no other food will compare to its richness.

"And if I took on the planet, will I pay my dues"
- Now he is considering of taking on the world and going on a global round trip just to find the taste of it again. The dues in this scenario would refer to two things: one, the most obvious, is the longing to experience the taste again. The other, and more underlying and can easily escape the less versed, is the contemplation if he will have enough money to last until he could find the taste again.

"Your love was a mystery, yeah my love is a fool"
- Obviously the chicken has no emotion and therefore emits an enigmatic presence that does not coincide with Joji's desires. This is why he finds its "love" mysterious, for it has no love and is merely an object for consumption, thus fueling the delusion theory even further, made apparent with the line "my love is a fool". At this point, he is well aware of his insanity, but refuses to let it go.

"And I travel the country just to get to you."
- The considerations are over. Now he has full intent to travel the world to find the chicken. He has travelled the country and failed; now it was time to travel to new horizons and taste the world. With insanity keeping his obsession in check, he is ready and able to see it all until the end. For delicious chicken.



TL;DR - Run is about Joji entering into a phase of existential crisis from tasting what is, quite possibly, the best fried chicken in the world. The song highlights his delusions, from his obsession in finding the taste again to giving the fried chicken in question human qualities in order to justify his insanity. This insanity bears Joji to do extremes he has never done before. The conclusion of his "dream sequence" of crashing through a glass pane/window is actually him forcing his way through a closed KFC restaurant.
